<http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-75815/R-HSA-75815>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> , <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0043161> ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment>
                "Cyclin D turnover is regulated by ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation which are positively regulated by cyclin D phosphorylation on threonine-286 (Diehl et al., 1997).<p>After the Cyclin D serves the role of mediating reactions by Cdk4 and Cdk6, it is shuttled to the cytoplasm and degraded in a ubiquitin-dependent manner. Whether Cdk4 and Cdk6 are truly redundant is a topic still under investigation, although both the kinases are required for normal cell cycle progression.<p>Destruction of the D type cyclins accompanies the end of the G1 phase, and the E type cyclins are involved in transition of the cell from G1 to S phase." ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Ubiquitin-dependent degradation of Cyclin D" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor>
                "GOC:reactome_curators" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date>
                "2026-02-25" ;
        <http://purl.org/pav/providedBy>
                "https://reactome.org" ;
        <http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref>
                "R-HSA-75815" ;
